Introduction

Dealing with categorical data in R

Recall:

A categorical variable is data that takes a limited or finite set of possible values. Assignment of observation to a group or nominal category is often based on a qualitative property. (e.g.Â gender, marital status, race)

Dealing with categorical data in R

Categorical variables are stored in R either as character strings or factors.

Factors are integer vectors that are mapped to categorical values. Factors contain a levels attribute, which is the order at which categorical values are assigned to integers.

Dealing with categorical data in R

Suppose we have a variable called rate that takes on the values low, medium, and high. When stored as a character vector, R sorts the values by alphabetical order.

rate <- c("low", "medium", "high")
sort(rate)

## [1] "high"   "low"    "medium"

When converted into a factor, R will provide additional information on the variable levels.

rate_factor <- as.factor(rate)

## [1] low    medium high  
## Levels: high low medium

Dealing with categorical data in R

To illustrate the mapping of categorical values to integers, we will recover numeric information from rate_factor:

rate_level <- as.numeric(rate_factor)

rate rate_level
low 2
medium 3
high 1


Note that if we do this for the original vector, we will not be able to extract any numeric information.

as.numeric(rate)

## [1] NA NA NA

Sample

R displays factor information in charts (and tables) based on the variableâs defined levels.

While the chart was already quite informative, we may want to present the order of our variable in another manner.

Reordering factors

A. Reordering (manual)

We can reorder factor levels based on our desired arrangement.

One option is to reorder factors manually using the fct_relevel() function.

The following arguments need to be specified:
1. the factor of interest (as a vector)
2. the desired factor order

Recall, the levels of the marital variable:

## [1] "No answer"     "Never married" "Separated"     "Divorced"     
## [5] "Widowed"       "Married"

A. Reordering (manual)

If we want the category Married to be the first level, we can do so by specifying it as the second argument:

fct_relevel(data$marital, "Married")

## [1] "Married"       "No answer"     "Never married" "Separated"    
## [5] "Divorced"      "Widowed"

We can also use the argument after to specify a position. This places Widowed after the 2nd level or in the 3rd place:

fct_relevel(data$marital, "Widowed", after = 2)

## [1] "Married"       "No answer"     "Widowed"       "Never married"
## [5] "Separated"     "Divorced"

This places No answer in the last place:

fct_relevel(data$marital, "No answer", after = Inf)

## [1] "Married"       "Widowed"       "Never married" "Separated"    
## [5] "Divorced"      "No answer"

A. Reordering (manual)

B. Reordering (variable-based)

We can also reorder a factor based on another variable.

Suppose we want to plot marital status against another variable, tvhours, to determine the average number of hours spent watching TV by each group.

B. Reordering (variable-based)

B. Reordering (variable-based)

We can make the chart more readable by reporting the marital variable in order of average tvhours.

For variable-based reordering, we use the function fct_reorder().

The following arguments need to be specified:
1. the factor of interest (as a vector)
2. the variable to base the order on

levels(data$marital)

## [1] "Married"       "Widowed"       "Never married" "Separated"    
## [5] "Divorced"      "No answer"

fct_reorder(data$marital, data$tvhours)

## [1] "No answer"     "Married"       "Divorced"      "Never married"
## [5] "Widowed"       "Separated"

B. Reordering (variable-based)

C. Reordering (frequency-based)

We can also reorder factors based on frequency.

Suppose we want have a look at number of time each marital category appears in the sample.

Marital Status 2000 2014
Married 1278 1158
Widowed 273 209
Never married 712 675
Separated 112 81
Divorced 441 411
No answer 1 4

C. Reordering (frequency-based)

C. Reordering (frequency-based)

We can easily reorder the levels based on how frequent a value appears on the sample using the function fct_infreq().

levels(data$marital)

## [1] "Married"       "Widowed"       "Never married" "Separated"    
## [5] "Divorced"      "No answer"

fct_infreq(data$marital)

## [1] "Married"       "Never married" "Divorced"      "Widowed"      
## [5] "Separated"     "No answer"

C. Reordering (frequency-based)

D. Reordering (reverse)

Another useful function is reversing the order of levels using fct_rev().

levels(data$marital)

## [1] "Married"       "Never married" "Divorced"      "Widowed"      
## [5] "Separated"     "No answer"

fct_rev(data$marital)

## [1] "No answer"     "Separated"     "Widowed"       "Divorced"     
## [5] "Never married" "Married"

D. Reordering (reverse)

Renaming factors

Renaming factors

Another useful feature of forcats is changing level values. Doing so makes labels clearer for data visualization and also allows us to collapse and combine levels.

Take for example the partyid variable which shows the respondentâs party affiliation.

Party % Share
No answer 0.72
Donât know 0.00
Other party 1.83
Strong republican 10.77
Not str republican 14.11
Ind,near rep 8.34
Independent 19.17
Ind,near dem 11.63
Not str democrat 17.18
Strong democrat 16.25

Renaming factors

A. Renaming (recoding)

The partyid variable has 10 levels, three of which are not specifically defined -
No answer, Donât know, and Other party.

What we may want to do is combine these three into a single category. We can use the function fct_recode() to change the labels of the factor levels.

The following arguments need to be specified:
1. the factor of interest (as a vector)
2. mapping of new and old factor values

data %>%
mutate(fct_recode(partyid,
"Other" = "No answer",
"Other" = "Don't know",
"Other" = "Other party"))

A. Renaming (recoding)

A. Renaming (recoding)

We can also use the fct_recode() function to clean up and standardize the values of the factors.

data %>% mutate(partyid = fct_recode(partyid,
"Republican, strong" = "Strong republican",
"Republican, weak" = "Not str republican",
"Independent, near rep" = "Ind,near rep",
"Independent, near dem" = "Ind,near dem",
"Democrat, weak" = "Not str democrat",
"Democrat, strong" = "Strong democrat"))

A. Renaming (recoding)

B. Renaming (collapsing)

For combining multiple levels together, and even more useful function is fct_collapse().

The function allows us to map the new value to a vector of old values.

So if we want to combine all Republicans, Democrats and Independents:

data %>%
mutate(partyid = fct_collapse(partyid,
Republican = str_subset(data$partyid, "Republican"),
Independent = str_subset(data$partyid, "Independent"),
Democrat = str_subset(data$partyid, "Democrat")))

B. Renaming (collapsing)

C. Renaming (lumping)

If there are no specific values that we want to collapse together, we may also want to just lump the smallest values into a single category.

To do this we use the fct_lump() function.

The following arguments need to be specified:
1. the factor of interest (as a vector)
2. the number of categories that we want to retain

C. Renaming (lumping)

We have the original table:

Party % Share
No answer 0.72
Donât know 0.00
Other party 1.83
Strong republican 10.77
Not str republican 14.11
Ind,near rep 8.34
Independent 19.17
Ind,near dem 11.63
Not str democrat 17.18
Strong democrat 16.25

C. Renaming (lumping)

And we want to retain only the top 4 categories and move the rest to the “Other” category.

data %>% mutate(partyid = fct_lump(partyid, n = 4))

Party % Share
Not str republican 14.11
Independent 19.17
Not str democrat 17.18
Strong democrat 16.25
Other 33.29

C. Renaming (lumping)

C. Renaming (lumping)

As a review, we reorder the factor based on the share:

data %>% mutate(partyid = fct_reorder(partyid, share))

C. Renaming (lumping)

Summary

forcats functions

For reordering factors:

  1. fct_relevel() - for reordering factors manually or by hand
  2. fct_reorder() - for reordering factors based on another variable
  3. fct_infreq() - for reordering factors based on frequency
  4. fct_rev() - for reversing the order of factors


For renaming factors:

  1. fct_recode() - for renaming factor levels manually or by hand
  2. fct_collapse() - for combining multiple factor levels
  3. fct_lump() - for combining most infrequent factor levels
